---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
---
<DocsLayout title="Project Configuration — Band Docs">
  <h1>Project Configuration</h1>

  <p>
    Each Band project can include a <code>.band/config.json</code> file at the repository root.
    This file defines shell scripts that run during workspace lifecycle events. Commit it to the
    repository so that all team members share the same workspace setup.
  </p>

  <h2>File Location</h2>

  <p>
    The configuration file lives at <code>&lt;project-root&gt;/.band/config.json</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>Schema</h2>

  <p>The top-level structure of the configuration file:</p>

  <pre><code set:html={`{'{'}
  "setup": ["npm install", "npm run db:migrate"],
  "teardown": ["npm run db:reset"]
{'}'}`}></code></pre>

  <h2>Setup Scripts</h2>

  <p>
    The <code>setup</code> array contains shell commands that run after a workspace is created
    via <code>band workspaces create</code>. Commands execute sequentially in the new worktree
    directory.
  </p>

  <pre><code>"setup": [
  "npm install",
  "npm run db:migrate",
  "cp .env.example .env"
]</code></pre>

  <p>
    Use setup scripts for dependency installation, database migrations, environment file
    creation, or any other initialization your project needs. Setup failures are non-fatal —
    the workspace is still created.
  </p>

  <h2>Teardown Scripts</h2>

  <p>
    The <code>teardown</code> array contains shell commands that run before a workspace is
    removed via <code>band workspaces remove</code>. Use these for cleanup tasks like stopping
    background services or resetting databases.
  </p>

  <pre><code>"teardown": [
  "docker compose down",
  "npm run db:reset"
]</code></pre>

  <h2>Full Example</h2>

  <pre><code set:html={`{'{'}
  "setup": [
    "npm install",
    "npx prisma db push",
    "cp .env.example .env.local"
  ],
  "teardown": [
    "docker compose down -v"
  ]
{'}'}`}></code></pre>
</DocsLayout>
